<h2 class="wp-block-heading has-text-align-center">STM32 FreeRTOS Stack Overflow Hook: CubeMX Setup</h2>



<p>The stack overflow detection is not enabled by default. We need to first enable it ourselves in the STM32CubeMX.</p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Enabling Stack Overflow Hook in CubeMX</h3>



<p>Go to Middleware &gt; FreeRTOS &gt; Config Parameters and find the section <strong>Hook Function Related Definitions</strong>. Look for the parameter <strong>Check for Stack Overflow Hook</strong>. By default, it is disabled.</p>



<p>Enable it and select <strong>Option 2</strong> from the dropdown. This activates automatic stack overflow detection.</p>


<div class="wp-block-image">
<figure class="aligncenter size-full is-resized"><a ref="magnificPopup" href="https://controllerstech.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/stm32_cmsis_rtos_8_12.webp" target="_blank" rel=" noreferrer noopener"><img loading="lazy" decoding="async" width="714" height="465" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAAAAACH5BAEKAAEALAAAAAABAAEAAAICTAEAOw==" alt="Image shows how to enable CHECK FOR STACK OVERFLOW in STM32CubeMX." class="wp-image-160568 lazyload" style="width:500px" data-src="https://controllerstech.com/wp-content/uploads/2026/04/stm32_cmsis_rtos_8_12.webp"></a></figure>
</div>


<div style="height:10px" aria-hidden="true" class="wp-block-spacer"></div>



<p>When enabled, a function called <code>vApplicationStackOverflowHook</code> is automatically generated in the FreeRTOS.c file. We need to write the implementation code inside this function to handle overflow events.</p>



<hr class="wp-sep-h3-dashed" />



<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Option 1 vs Option 2 Detection Methods</h3>



<p>FreeRTOS provides two detection methods:</p>



<p><strong>Option 1</strong>: Checks if the stack pointer has gone out of bounds at every task context switch. This method is faster but may miss overflows that happen between context switches.</p>



<p><strong>Option 2</strong>: Uses a pattern or marker value placed at the end of the stack to detect overflows more reliably. This method catches more overflow events because it checks continuously, not just during context switches. Option 2 uses slightly more processing power but provides better detection accuracy.</p>



<p>For most projects, Option 2 is recommended because it catches stack overflows more reliably.</p>



<hr class="wp-sep-h3-dashed" />



<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Creating vApplicationStackOverflowHook Function</h3>



<p>After enabling the hook in CubeMX and regenerating the code, open the FreeRTOS.c file. Find the <code>vApplicationStackOverflowHook</code> function:</p>



