<h2 class="wp-block-heading has-text-align-center">STM32 FreeRTOS Stack Management FAQs</h2>


<div class="wp-block-uagb-faq uagb-faq__outer-wrap uagb-block-fdafe3eb uagb-faq-icon-row uagb-faq-layout-accordion uagb-faq-expand-first-false uagb-faq-inactive-other-true uagb-faq__wrap uagb-buttons-layout-wrap uagb-faq-equal-height     " data-faqtoggle="true" role="tablist"><script type="application/ld+json">{"@context":"https:\/\/schema.org","@type":"FAQPage","@id":"https:\/\/controllerstech.com\/stm32-freertos-stack-management-monitor-detect-overflow\/","mainEntity":[{"@type":"Question","name":"<strong><strong>Can I use printf() inside the stack overflow hook function?<\/strong><\/strong>","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"No. The <code>printf()<\/code> function relies on complex buffering and interrupt mechanisms that may not work properly in the critical overflow context. Always use direct UART transmission with <code>HAL_UART_Transmit()<\/code> instead. This is why we re-initialize the UART before sending the error message."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"<strong><strong><strong><strong><strong>Why does the high water mark sometimes stay the same even after I add more code to a task?<\/strong><\/strong><\/strong><\/strong><\/strong>","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"The high water mark only changes when a task uses more stack than its previous worst case. If your new code doesn't reach deeper into the stack than existing code paths, the high water mark remains unchanged. You need to test all possible execution paths in your task to see the true worst-case scenario."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"<strong><strong><strong><strong>What stack size should I allocate to the monitor task itself?<\/strong><\/strong><\/strong><\/strong>","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"The monitor task needs a larger stack than your application tasks because it must accommodate the <code>printf()<\/code> function, which consumes significant memory. Allocate at least 512 words to the monitor task. Since it runs at low priority, it does not interfere with other tasks."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"<strong><strong><strong>Can stack overflow detection miss some overflow events?<\/strong><\/strong><\/strong>","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Option 2 is very reliable, but it checks the stack marker periodically, not continuously. Extremely fast overflows that corrupt and recover within microseconds might theoretically be missed. However, this is extremely rare in practice. For safety-critical systems, combine the overflow hook with runtime monitoring of high water mark values."}},{"@type":"Question","name":"<strong><strong><strong>Does enabling stack overflow detection consume significant CPU time?<\/strong><\/strong><\/strong>","acceptedAnswer":{"@type":"Answer","text":"Option 2 adds minimal overhead because it only checks the marker during context switches and specific FreeRTOS operations. The performance impact is negligible. Disable it only in production if you have already verified stack sizes are safe and need maximum performance."}}]}</script><div class="wp-block-uagb-faq-child uagb-faq-child__outer-wrap uagb-faq-item uagb-block-60c47f60 " role="tab" tabindex="0"><div class="uagb-faq-questions-button uagb-faq-questions">			<span class="uagb-icon uagb-faq-icon-wrap">
