							</span>
			<span class="uagb-question"><strong><strong>Can I use printf() inside the stack overflow hook function?</strong></strong></span></div><div class="uagb-faq-content"><p>No. The <code>printf()</code> function relies on complex buffering and interrupt mechanisms that may not work properly in the critical overflow context. Always use direct UART transmission with <code>HAL_UART_Transmit()</code> instead. This is why we re-initialize the UART before sending the error message.</p></div></div><div class="wp-block-uagb-faq-child uagb-faq-child__outer-wrap uagb-faq-item uagb-block-4c106fb6 " role="tab" tabindex="0"><div class="uagb-faq-questions-button uagb-faq-questions">			<span class="uagb-icon uagb-faq-icon-wrap">
								<svg xmlns="https://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox= "0 0 448 512"><path d="M432 256c0 17.69-14.33 32.01-32 32.01H256v144c0 17.69-14.33 31.99-32 31.99s-32-14.3-32-31.99v-144H48c-17.67 0-32-14.32-32-32.01s14.33-31.99 32-31.99H192v-144c0-17.69 14.33-32.01 32-32.01s32 14.32 32 32.01v144h144C417.7 224 432 238.3 432 256z"></path></svg>
							</span>
						<span class="uagb-icon-active uagb-faq-icon-wrap">
								<svg xmlns="https://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox= "0 0 448 512"><path d="M400 288h-352c-17.69 0-32-14.32-32-32.01s14.31-31.99 32-31.99h352c17.69 0 32 14.3 32 31.99S417.7 288 400 288z"></path></svg>
							</span>
			<span class="uagb-question"><strong><strong><strong><strong><strong>Why does the high water mark sometimes stay the same even after I add more code to a task?</strong></strong></strong></strong></strong></span></div><div class="uagb-faq-content"><p>The high water mark only changes when a task uses more stack than its previous worst case. If your new code doesn't reach deeper into the stack than existing code paths, the high water mark remains unchanged. You need to test all possible execution paths in your task to see the true worst-case scenario.</p></div></div><div class="wp-block-uagb-faq-child uagb-faq-child__outer-wrap uagb-faq-item uagb-block-19803995 " role="tab" tabindex="0"><div class="uagb-faq-questions-button uagb-faq-questions">			<span class="uagb-icon uagb-faq-icon-wrap">
								<svg xmlns="https://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox= "0 0 448 512"><path d="M432 256c0 17.69-14.33 32.01-32 32.01H256v144c0 17.69-14.33 31.99-32 31.99s-32-14.3-32-31.99v-144H48c-17.67 0-32-14.32-32-32.01s14.33-31.99 32-31.99H192v-144c0-17.69 14.33-32.01 32-32.01s32 14.32 32 32.01v144h144C417.7 224 432 238.3 432 256z"></path></svg>
							</span>
						<span class="uagb-icon-active uagb-faq-icon-wrap">
								<svg xmlns="https://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox= "0 0 448 512"><path d="M400 288h-352c-17.69 0-32-14.32-32-32.01s14.31-31.99 32-31.99h352c17.69 0 32 14.3 32 31.99S417.7 288 400 288z"></path></svg>
							</span>
			<span class="uagb-question"><strong><strong><strong><strong>What stack size should I allocate to the monitor task itself?</strong></strong></strong></strong></span></div><div class="uagb-faq-content"><p>The monitor task needs a larger stack than your application tasks because it must accommodate the <code>printf()</code> function, which consumes significant memory. Allocate at least 512 words to the monitor task. Since it runs at low priority, it does not interfere with other tasks.</p></div></div><div class="wp-block-uagb-faq-child uagb-faq-child__outer-wrap uagb-faq-item uagb-block-948bfce1 " role="tab" tabindex="0"><div class="uagb-faq-questions-button uagb-faq-questions">			<span class="uagb-icon uagb-faq-icon-wrap">
								<svg xmlns="https://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox= "0 0 448 512"><path d="M432 256c0 17.69-14.33 32.01-32 32.01H256v144c0 17.69-14.33 31.99-32 31.99s-32-14.3-32-31.99v-144H48c-17.67 0-32-14.32-32-32.01s14.33-31.99 32-31.99H192v-144c0-17.69 14.33-32.01 32-32.01s32 14.32 32 32.01v144h144C417.7 224 432 238.3 432 256z"></path></svg>
							</span>
						<span class="uagb-icon-active uagb-faq-icon-wrap">
								<svg xmlns="https://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox= "0 0 448 512"><path d="M400 288h-352c-17.69 0-32-14.32-32-32.01s14.31-31.99 32-31.99h352c17.69 0 32 14.3 32 31.99S417.7 288 400 288z"></path></svg>
							</span>
			<span class="uagb-question"><strong><strong><strong>Can stack overflow detection miss some overflow events?</strong></strong></strong></span></div><div class="uagb-faq-content"><p>Option 2 is very reliable, but it checks the stack marker periodically, not continuously. Extremely fast overflows that corrupt and recover within microseconds might theoretically be missed. However, this is extremely rare in practice. For safety-critical systems, combine the overflow hook with runtime monitoring of high water mark values.</p></div></div><div class="wp-block-uagb-faq-child uagb-faq-child__outer-wrap uagb-faq-item uagb-block-ee6f75fc " role="tab" tabindex="0"><div class="uagb-faq-questions-button uagb-faq-questions">			<span class="uagb-icon uagb-faq-icon-wrap">
								<svg xmlns="https://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox= "0 0 448 512"><path d="M432 256c0 17.69-14.33 32.01-32 32.01H256v144c0 17.69-14.33 31.99-32 31.99s-32-14.3-32-31.99v-144H48c-17.67 0-32-14.32-32-32.01s14.33-31.99 32-31.99H192v-144c0-17.69 14.33-32.01 32-32.01s32 14.32 32 32.01v144h144C417.7 224 432 238.3 432 256z"></path></svg>
							</span>
						<span class="uagb-icon-active uagb-faq-icon-wrap">
								<svg xmlns="https://www.w3.org/2000/svg" viewBox= "0 0 448 512"><path d="M400 288h-352c-17.69 0-32-14.32-32-32.01s14.31-31.99 32-31.99h352c17.69 0 32 14.3 32 31.99S417.7 288 400 288z"></path></svg>
							</span>
			<span class="uagb-question"><strong><strong><strong>Does enabling stack overflow detection consume significant CPU time?</strong></strong></strong></span></div><div class="uagb-faq-content"><p>Option 2 adds minimal overhead because it only checks the marker during context switches and specific FreeRTOS operations. The performance impact is negligible. Disable it only in production if you have already verified stack sizes are safe and need maximum performance.</p></div></div></div>


